TAB.TITLE: MSL Surface Analysis
TAB.HELPTEXT:
The MSL surface analysis is issued every three hours by a forecaster at the Weather Prediction Center (WPC).
    This analysis is valid at the synoptic times of 0000Z, 0300Z, 0600Z, ..., 2100Z. The latest surface
    analysis becomes available at approximately 90 minutes after these synoptic times. Included are a national loop covering the
    conterminous U.S. as well as regional loops. When a region is selected the most recent surface analysis imgage available is
    initially shown. Each loop spans a time of approximately 24 hours beginning with the oldest analysis and ending with the
    most recent analysis. Please see <a href="https://www.wpc.ncep.noaa.gov/html/fntcodes2.shtml" TARGET="_blank">this</a>
    page for a legend of surface fronts and boundaries depicted in these surface analysis charts.  For guidance on
    how to read the surface station models, please see <a href="https://www.wpc.ncep.noaa.gov/html/stationplot.shtml" TARGET="_blank">this</a> page.
    <br><br>See the <a href="https://s3-static.ezwxbrief.com/PG/EZWxBrief-Pilots-Guide.pdf" TARGET="_blank">EZWxBrief Pilots Guide</a> for more information.

TAB.TITLE: National Forecast Chart
TAB.HELPTEXT:
The National Forecast Chart is issued by a forecaster at the Weather Prediction Center (WPC) and provides an overview of expected weather
    for up to the next three days, with emphasis on certain hazardous and significant weather. They summarize forecasts from several
    NCEP Service Centers including the Storm Prediction Center (for severe thunderstorm and tornado outlooks as well as critical fire weather), the National Hurricane
    Center (for tropical storm and hurricane forecasts), and the Weather Prediction Center (for information concerning heavy rainfall,
    flooding, winter weather, and general weather). With overlaid frontal forecasts, these displays serve as a good overview of the
    expected weather for the next three days.  Note: Fronts depicted on this forecast are valid at a single time that occurs at the
    beginning of the valid date-time stamp.  Weather areas are valid over a 12 hour period defined by the valid range shown.
    <br><br>See the <a href="https://s3-static.ezwxbrief.com/PG/EZWxBrief-Pilots-Guide.pdf" TARGET="_blank">EZWxBrief Pilots Guide</a> for more information.

TAB.TITLE: Prog Charts
TAB.HELPTEXT:
Short and extended range forecasts are also known as "prog" charts.  Meteorologists at the Weather Prediction Center (WPC)
    prepare 6 through 60 hour forecasts for the conterminous U.S., southern Canada, and northern Mexico.  These short range forecasts are
    issued twice a day at <a href="https://www.wpc.ncep.noaa.gov/basicwx/about_bawx.shtml" TARGET="_blank">these</a> times and
    include surface pressure patterns (isobars), circulation centers (highs and lows) and fronts for 6 through 60 hours. A depiction of the
    types, extent (coverage) and likelihood of precipitation are a mosaic extracted from the National Digital Forecast Database (NDFD) and
    is prepared by forecasters at the NWS Weather Forecast Offices in collaboration with the WPC.  The primary goal is to depict accurately
    the evolution of major weather systems that will affect the conterminous U.S. during the next 6 to 60 hours. Precipitation for the short 
	range forecasts are valid at the time depicted on the chart representing precipitation coverage. 
    For guidance on precipitation areas used in these short range forecasts, please
    see <a href="https://www.wpc.ncep.noaa.gov/basicwx/about_ndfd_graphics.shtml" TARGET="_blank">this</a> page.
    <br><br>Extended range forecasts are also issued by forecasters at the WPC at <a href="https://www.wpc.ncep.noaa.gov/medr/about_medr.shtml" TARGET="_blank">these</a> times. Only surface pressure patterns, circulation centers, and fronts are depicted from 72 hours (Day 3) through 168 hours (Day 7) and are valid at the time depicted on the chart. Precipitation on the extended range forecasts are valid over a range of time from 1800Z to 0000Z. Therefore, the areal coverage will be generally larger than the short range forecast for precipitation as it is based on the 6-hour probability of precipitation (PoP). See <a href="https://www.wpc.ncep.noaa.gov/html/fntcodes2.shtml" TARGET="_blank">this</a> page for a legend of surface fronts and other symbology used in these short and extended range forecasts. 
	<br><br>See the <a href="https://s3-static.ezwxbrief.com/PG/EZWxBrief-Pilots-Guide.pdf" TARGET="_blank">EZWxBrief Pilots Guide</a> for more information.

TAB.TITLE: 6 hour QPF
TAB.HELPTEXT:
This is the Quantitative Precipitation Forecast or QPF.  The QPF is an accumulated precipitation forecast
    valid over a specific range of time, in this case, six hours.  These forecasts depict isohyets (colored contours) of
    accumulated precipitation of 0.01, 0.25, 0.50, 1 inch and so on expected in each six hour period. Keep in mind, this
    precipitation forecast is the liquid equivalent expected to reach the surface and does not distinguish between precipitation
    type (snow, rain, ice pellets, etc.) or whether the precipitation is convective or non-convective. While this is not a
    probabilistic forecast, meteorologists will generally only include contours on this chart when there's a high confidence
    (generally greater than 50 percent) of measurable precipitation reaching the surface. <br><br>See the <a href="https://s3-static.ezwxbrief.com/PG/EZWxBrief-Pilots-Guide.pdf" TARGET="_blank">EZWxBrief Pilots Guide</a> for more information.

TAB.TITLE: Prob of Precipitation
TAB.HELPTEXT:
This is the 12-hour Probability of Precipitation (PoP) extended range forecast for Day 3 through Day 7.
    These forecasts are issued twice a day by meteorologists at the Weather Prediction Center (WPC).  Higher
    numbers denote high forecaster confidence that measurable precipitation will reach the surface within the valid
    12-hour forecast period.  The 12-hour forecast periods generally coincide with a nighttime (00Z to 12Z)
    and a daytime (12Z to 00Z) period.  Please note that the valid timestamp on the chart is the ending time
    of the 12-hour forecast period. <br><br>See the <a href="https://s3-static.ezwxbrief.com/PG/EZWxBrief-Pilots-Guide.pdf" TARGET="_blank">EZWxBrief Pilots Guide</a> for more information.

TAB.TITLE: MRMS Composite Reflectivity
TAB.HELPTEXT:
This is the quality controlled composite radar mosaic loop over the last three hours for the conterminous U.S. 
	from the Multi-radar/Multi-sensor (MRMS) product. <br><br>See the <a href="https://s3-static.ezwxbrief.com/PG/EZWxBrief-Pilots-Guide.pdf" TARGET="_blank">EZWxBrief Pilots Guide</a> for more information.

TAB.TITLE: Pilot Reports
TAB.HELPTEXT:
The latest routine and urgent pilot weather reports (PIREPs) for the conterminous U.S. for airframe ice, turbulence and weather and
    sky conditions.  Please note that pilot weather reports are looped from the oldest reports to the most recent reports. Urgent PIREPs
    are shown in red. See <a href="https://aviationweather.gov/airep/help?page=plot" TARGET="_blank">this</a> page
    for more information on the symbology used on these charts. <br><br>See the <a href="https://s3-static.ezwxbrief.com/PG/EZWxBrief-Pilots-Guide.pdf" TARGET="_blank">EZWxBrief Pilots Guide</a> for more information.

TAB.TITLE: Visible Satellite
TAB.HELPTEXT:
This is the visible satellite image.  Satellite images are provide every 15 minutes and are available
    during the daytime by geographic region including a National image. Therefore, nocturnal images will rendered in black.
    When a region is selected the most recent satellite image available is initially shown.  The loop will provide a
    historical reference from oldest to most recent for the last eight hours. <br><br>See the <a href="https://s3-static.ezwxbrief.com/PG/EZWxBrief-Pilots-Guide.pdf" TARGET="_blank">EZWxBrief Pilots Guide</a> for more information.

TAB.TITLE: Infrared Satellite
TAB.HELPTEXT:
This is the color-enhanced infrared satellite image.  Satellite images are provided every 15 minutes and are
    available throughout the day and night by geographic region as well as a National image. When a region is selected the latest image available is shown.
    The loop will provide a historical reference from oldest to most recent for the last eight hours.  Colors shown on this image
    represent the temperature of the cloud top in degrees Celsius or in cloud-free air, the temperature of the surface of the earth.
    <br><br>See the <a href="https://s3-static.ezwxbrief.com/PG/EZWxBrief-Pilots-Guide.pdf" TARGET="_blank">EZWxBrief Pilots Guide</a> for more information.

TAB.TITLE: SIGMETs
TAB.HELPTEXT:
SIGMETs are en route advisories for significant meteorological information.  When issued, they are valid for a 4 hour period.
    A historical loop is provided over the previous 5 hours ordered from oldest to newest.  This includes SIGMETs for widespread severe
    non-convective airframe ice, severe or extreme non-convective turbulence and dust storms or sandstorms.  These are issued on an as-needed
    basis by forecasters at the Aviation Weather Center (AWC). <br><br>SIGMETs are also issued for convection meeting convective SIGMET criteria
    that includes an area of convection at least 3,000 square miles with at least 40% coverage in that area, a line of convection at least
    60 nautical miles long with at least 40% coverage along that line, an area of embedded thunderstorms or thunderstorms that are designated
    by a forecaster at the local Weather Forecast Office as severe.  Convective SIGMETS are routinely issued at 55 minutes past each hour
    or on an as-needed basis during rapidly developing convective events.  They are valid for a two hour period or may be updated or terminated
    with the next issuance. <br><br>See the <a href="https://s3-static.ezwxbrief.com/PG/EZWxBrief-Pilots-Guide.pdf" TARGET="_blank">EZWxBrief Pilots Guide</a> for more information.

TAB.TITLE: Graphical AIRMETs
TAB.HELPTEXT:
Graphical AIRMETs or G-AIRMETs are en route advisories issued for adverse weather conditions that are not 
expected to meet National SIGMET criteria. This encompasses advisories for the freezing level (and multiple freezing levels),
widespread moderate non-convective airframe ice, widespread moderate non-convective turbulence (high and low altitude), widespread
strong sustained surface winds greater than 30 knots, widespread non-convective low level wind shear (LLWS) below 2,000 feet AGL
and widespread IFR conditions and mountain obscuration. Widespread defines an area greater than 3,000 square miles. G-AIRMETs
are routinely issued by forecasters at the Aviation Weather Center (AWC) every six hours at 0245Z, 0845Z, 1445Z and 2045Z and
amended as necessary. Every G-AIRMET issuance provides five snapshots each valid at a single time. Therefore, this is a forecast for
coverage of a particular adverse weather element at the valid time on the chart. This includes an initial snapshot and forecasts with a lead
time of 3, 6, 9 and 12 hours. <br><br>See the <a href="https://s3-static.ezwxbrief.com/PG/EZWxBrief-Pilots-Guide.pdf" TARGET="_blank">EZWxBrief Pilots Guide</a> for more information.

TAB.TITLE: Cloud Top Heights
TAB.HELPTEXT:
This is the MSL height forecast of the cloud tops in 5,000 ft intervals for lead times
    of 1, 2, 3, 6, 9, 12, 15 and 18 hours.  This forecast guidance is based on numerical model forecasts
    from the Rapid Refresh (RAP) model and is issued hourly. <br><br>See the <a href="https://s3-static.ezwxbrief.com/PG/EZWxBrief-Pilots-Guide.pdf" TARGET="_blank">EZWxBrief Pilots Guide</a> for more information.

TAB.TITLE: US GFA
TAB.HELPTEXT:
Provides static imagery for the Graphical Forecasts for Aviation (GFA) for clouds and surface conditions over the conterminous U.S.
    This provided forecast guidance with lead times of 3, 6, 9, 12, 15 and 18 hours. Included are graphics of surface visibility depicted in colored contours, overlays of
    surface wind and gusts depicted with standard wind barbs, overlays of predominant weather type (i.e., haze, fog, smoke, blowing dust/sand),
    overlays of Graphical AIRMETs to include Instrument Flight Rules (IFR) and Strong Surface Wind, and overlays of predominant precipitation type
    (i.e., rain, snow, mix, ice, or thunderstorm) coincident with any cloud (see <a href="https://www.aviationweather.gov/metar/symbol" TARGET="_blank">this</a> page).
    <br><br>See the <a href="https://s3-static.ezwxbrief.com/PG/EZWxBrief-Pilots-Guide.pdf" TARGET="_blank">EZWxBrief Pilots Guide</a> for more information.

TAB.TITLE: Canada GFA
TAB.HELPTEXT:
Provides static imagery for the Graphical Area Forecast (GFA) for clouds, weather, turbulence and icing over Canada.
    This includes a 0, 6 and 12 hour forecast. <br><br>See the <a href="https://s3-static.ezwxbrief.com/PG/EZWxBrief-Pilots-Guide.pdf" TARGET="_blank">EZWxBrief Pilots Guide</a> for more information.

TAB.TITLE: Gridded LAMP MOS
TAB.HELPTEXT:
This is the graphical Model Output Statics (MOS) for the Local Aviation MOS program (LAMP) model including the convective and lightning probability forecasts.
    <br><br>See the <a href="https://s3-static.ezwxbrief.com/PG/EZWxBrief-Pilots-Guide.pdf" TARGET="_blank">EZWxBrief Pilots Guide</a> for more information.

TAB.TITLE: HREF Model
TAB.HELPTEXT:
Forecasts for the probability of a Marginal VFR (MVFR), IFR and Low IFR (LIFR) ceiling from the High Resolution Ensemble Forecast (HREF). This provides an hourly forecast
    over the next 48 hours and is updated four times throughout the day. Also includes the probabilities of ceilings below 3,000 ft, 2,000 ft and 1,000 ft as well as a probabilistic forecast for echo tops over 30,000 ft and 35,000 ft MSL. Also included is the simulated reflectivity forecast from the HREF model that provides a simulated reflectivity forecast over the next 48 hours for the conterminous U.S. It is run twice a day at 0000 and 1200 UTC and will become available about five or six hours after this time (approximately 0500 and 1700 UTC, respectively). <br><br>See the <a href="https://s3-static.ezwxbrief.com/PG/EZWxBrief-Pilots-Guide.pdf" TARGET="_blank">EZWxBrief Pilots Guide</a> for more information.

TAB.TITLE: GFS Model
TAB.HELPTEXT:
Forecasts generated by the Global Forecast System (GFS) numerical weather prediction model
    are provided for the latest execution cycles to include 0000, 0600, 1200 and 1800 UTC. In addition to the 
    analysis for the latest cycle, forecasts are provided through 120 hours (5 days).  This includes a forecast for 
    MSL pressure, 850 mb temperature (degrees Celsius) and 6-hour accumulated precipitation.  Precipitation 
    forecasts are valid during the six hours prior to the valid time shown on the chart. Additionally, a 
    constant pressure chart analysis and forecasts for 850 mb (~5,000 feet MSL), 700 mb (~10,000 feet MSL), 
    500 mb (~18,000 feet MSL), 300 mb (~30,000 feet MSL), 250 mb (~34,000 feet MSL) and 200 mb (~39,000 feet MSL) are also available. 
      Forecasts from this model are normally available between around four hours after the execution cycle times.  For example, the 1200 UTC 
    cycle ordinarily becomes available around 1600 UTC on average.  Please see 
    <a href="http://www.nco.ncep.noaa.gov/pmb/nwprod/prodstat_new" TARGET="_blank">this</a> page for 
    specific model run status. <br><br>See the <a href="https://s3-static.ezwxbrief.com/PG/EZWxBrief-Pilots-Guide.pdf" TARGET="_blank">EZWxBrief Pilots Guide</a> for more information.

TAB.TITLE: NAM Model
TAB.HELPTEXT:
Forecasts generated by the North American Mesoscale (NAM) numerical weather prediction model
are provided for the latest execution cycle to include 0000, 0600, 1200 and 1800 UTC. In addition to the 
analysis for the latest cycle, forecasts are available through 84 hours (3.5 days).  This includes a forecast for 
MSL pressure that also includes the 850 mb temperature (degrees Celsius) and 6-hour accumulated precipitation.  Precipitation 
forecasts are valid during the six hours prior to the valid time shown on the chart. Additionally, a 
constant pressure chart analysis and forecasts for 850 mb (~5,000 feet MSL), 700 mb (~10,000 feet MSL), 
500 mb (~18,000 feet MSL) and 300 mb (~30,000 feet MSL) are also available.  Forecasts from this model are 
normally available between two and three hours after the execution cycle times.  For example, the 1200 UTC 
cycle ordinarily becomes available around 1400 to 1500 UTC.  Please see 
<a href="http://www.nco.ncep.noaa.gov/pmb/nwprod/prodstat_new" TARGET="_blank">this</a> page for 
specific model run status.  Also included is lowest model layer simulated reflectivity from the most recent 
execution cycle of the high resolution North American Mesoscale (NAM) model. Forecasts for convective indices from the NAM are also provided.  This includes 
forecast for surface-based convective available potential energy (SBCAPE), most unstable convective available 
potential energy (MUCAPE), mixed layer convective available potential energy (MLCAPE) and most unstable 
lifted index (MULI).  The NAM also include a 3 km model resolution for simulated reflectivity overlaid on top of an IR satellite forecast.
The simulated reflectivity shows the expected precipitation type reaching the surface.  Forecasts are available at hourly intervals
through 60 hours. <br><br>See the <a href="https://s3-static.ezwxbrief.com/PG/EZWxBrief-Pilots-Guide.pdf" TARGET="_blank">EZWxBrief Pilots Guide</a> for more information.

TAB.TITLE: RAP/HRRR Model
TAB.HELPTEXT:
This is the simulated reflectivity forecast from the High Resolution Rapid Refresh (HRRR) model. The HRRR is run hourly
    and produces forecasts out to 15 hours using one hour and 15 minute forecast time steps.  Simulated reflectivity products provide forecasts at 1000 meters AGL.
    <br><br>See the <a href="https://s3-static.ezwxbrief.com/PG/EZWxBrief-Pilots-Guide.pdf" TARGET="_blank">EZWxBrief Pilots Guide</a> for more information.

TAB.TITLE: Storm Prediction Center
TAB.HELPTEXT:
Storm Prediction Center (SPC) convective outlooks and forecast products.  Day 1 means today, Day 2 means tomorrow,
    Day 3 is the following day. Severe thunderstorm or tornado watches (WW) are regions where active areas of severe thunderstorms
    including hail to 1 inch in diameter or greater, strong winds and tornadoes are possible. Clicking on any of the Day 1, Day 2, Day 3
    and Day 4-8 outlooks will bring up the outlook discussion in a separate window. Current mesoscale discussions (MD) represent areas
    that are likely for the development of strong storms, heavy rain or dangerous winter weather (heavy snow or ice).
    MDs may also contain a description of an event currently under a severe thunderstorm or tornado watch.  Enhanced resolution
    thunderstorm outlooks are valid over a four hour period (except for the overnight forecast from 0400 to 1200 UTC) and contain a
    probability forecast for general organized convective activity (severe or not). The thunderstorm probabilities take into account
    both the expected areal coverage and probability for thunder to occur. Therefore, a 40% probability means that given similar
    environmental conditions, thunder would be observed at any one location (in either a county or city) within the 40% thunder
    probability area four times out of ten, or 40% of the time. <br><br>See the <a href="https://s3-static.ezwxbrief.com/PG/EZWxBrief-Pilots-Guide.pdf" TARGET="_blank">EZWxBrief Pilots Guide</a> for more information.

TAB.TITLE: T-storm Probability Fcst
TAB.HELPTEXT:
This is the calibrated thunderstorm probability forecast from the Short Range Ensemble Forecast (SREF) model.
    Calibrated thunderstorm probability forecasts are available for a 1, 3 and 4 hour time period.  The date-time stamp on the
    chart is the <u>ending</u> time of the valid period.  For example, if the chart is valid at
    1500 UTC on the 23rd of the month, the valid period for the 3-hour calibrated thunderstorm probability forecast is from
    1200 UTC to 1500 UTC on that day.  <br><br>Contours shown on the chart are roughly equivalent to the probability of a thunderstorm
    within 10 miles of a point covering the 1, 3 or 4 hour time periods.  This product only shows the probability of convective events
    that produce lightning and may not cover all areas of deep, moist convection (DMC).  Also, the product does <u>not</u> forecast areas
    of non-convective precipitation.  White locations outside of the 3 or 5 percent contoured areas simply imply there is less than a 3 or 5 percent
    probability of thunderstorms.  In other words, it does not imply a zero percent probability. <br><br>See the <a href="https://s3-static.ezwxbrief.com/PG/EZWxBrief-Pilots-Guide.pdf" TARGET="_blank">EZWxBrief Pilots Guide</a> for more information.

TAB.TITLE: Convective Forecast Guidance
TAB.HELPTEXT:
This is the TFM Convective Forecast (TCF) guidance.  <br><br>Keep in mind that this is <strong>NOT</strong> a forecast for thunderstorms.  Moreover, the criteria used for
    CCFP is different than the criteria used for issuing convective SIGMETs (WSTs). <br><br>See the <a href="https://s3-static.ezwxbrief.com/PG/EZWxBrief-Pilots-Guide.pdf" TARGET="_blank">EZWxBrief Pilots Guide</a> for more information.

TAB.TITLE: Lowest Freezing Level
TAB.HELPTEXT:
This is an analysis and forecast of the lowest freezing level from the Rapid Refresh (RAP) model.
    The forecast and analysis is update hourly.  The RAP model produces forecasts from 1 to 18 hours at a one hour interval.
    The lowest freezing level is depicted at 2,000 ft. increments in hundreds of feet above mean sea level (MSL) using the
    scale at the bottom of the chart.  Areas depicted in white consist of regions where the entire temperature profile above
    the surface is below 0 degrees Celsius.  Hatched areas imply there are multiple freezing levels with the color presented
    in the hatched areas as the lowest freezing level. <br><br>See the <a href="https://s3-static.ezwxbrief.com/PG/EZWxBrief-Pilots-Guide.pdf" TARGET="_blank">EZWxBrief Pilots Guide</a> for more information.

TAB.TITLE: Icing Analyses
TAB.HELPTEXT:
This represents the latest CIP severity product looped by altitude with the composite (maximum) severity shown as the
    last image in the loop.<br><br>Icing scenario attempts to explain the cloud's microphysical-properties,
    especially clouds containing supercooled large water drops (SLD).  This can help to determine hazardous areas of
    potential in-flight aircraft icing. Here's a brief overview of the various icing scenario categories.<br><br><b>BWN:</b>
    Below warm nose - Classical FZRA structure with FZRA, PE, RA, FZDZ and/or DZ observed at the surface. The subfreezing layer resides beneath the
    melting layer (warm nose). Cloud top temperature (CTT) less than -12 degrees C.<br><br><b>AWN:</b> Above warm nose - Classical
    FZRA structure with FZRA, PE, RA, FZDZ and/or DZ observed at the surface. Cloudy area above melting layer (warm nose). Cloud top
    temperature (CTT) less than -12 degrees C.<br><br><b>AS:</b> All snow - All sounding levels less than 0 degrees C.  Snow
    is the only precipitation observed at the surface.<br><br><b>CR:</b> Cold rain - RA is observed at surface and
    Cloud Top Temp (CTT) less than or equal to -12 degrees C.<br><br><b>WMPCP:</b> Warm precipitation: Any non-snow
    precipitation observed at surface with a CTT greater than -12 degrees C.<br><br><b>CPCP:</b> Cold non-snow,
    non-rain - FZRA, PE, FZDZ and/or DZ observed at the surface with CTT greater than or equal to -12 degrees C.<br><br><b>CONV:</b>
    Convective - Lightning strikes within 25 km and 15 minutes. <br><br>See the <a href="https://s3-static.ezwxbrief.com/PG/EZWxBrief-Pilots-Guide.pdf" TARGET="_blank">EZWxBrief Pilots Guide</a> for more information.

TAB.TITLE: Icing Forecast by Altitude
TAB.HELPTEXT:
This is the Forecast Icing Product (FIP) that provides guidance for the probability of airframe icing and icing severity
    with a 1, 2, 3, 6, 9, 12, 15 and 18 hour lead time from the Rapid Refresh (RAP) forecast model. Each forecast hour provides a loop at 1,000 ft
    intervals altitude. Also included are forecast from the legacy Forecast Icing Product found on the Aviation Weather Center's website. This
    includes the Supercooled Large Drop (SLD) icing potential with an overlay in red on the icing severity forecast. See the EZWxBrief Pilots
    Guide for more information.

TAB.TITLE: Icing Forecast by Hour
TAB.HELPTEXT:
This is the Current Icing Product (CIP) and Forecast Icing Product (FIP) looped for the selected altitude for the CIP analysis and
    subsequent FIP forecasts through 18 hours. The first image is the CIP analysis followed by the FIP forecast for 1, 2, 3, 6, 9, 12, 15 and 18 hours. <br><br>See the <a href="https://s3-static.ezwxbrief.com/PG/EZWxBrief-Pilots-Guide.pdf" TARGET="_blank">EZWxBrief Pilots Guide</a> for more information.

TAB.TITLE: Icing Masked Severity
TAB.HELPTEXT:
This is the Current Icing Product (CIP) and Forecast Icing Product (FIP) 25-percent and 50-percent masked severity looped over an
    altitude for the CIP analysis and subsequent FIP forecasts through 18 hours.  Masked severity combines the probability product with the severity product.
    Areas with less than a 25-percent or 50-percent probability will be grayed out or masked to leave only the icing severity with the greatest
    probabilities. <br><br>See the <a href="https://s3-static.ezwxbrief.com/PG/EZWxBrief-Pilots-Guide.pdf" TARGET="_blank">EZWxBrief Pilots Guide</a> for more information.

TAB.TITLE: Turbulence by Altitude
TAB.HELPTEXT:
This is the Graphical Turbulence Guidance (GTG-3) product looped over an altitude.  Included are forecasts from the 13 km resolution
    RAP model for Clear Air Turbulence, Mountain Wave Turbulence and the combination of the two. <br><br>See the <a href="https://s3-static.ezwxbrief.com/PG/EZWxBrief-Pilots-Guide.pdf" TARGET="_blank">EZWxBrief Pilots Guide</a> for more information.
